div.div:
Observations:
All intermediary states are valid for reading, with the caveat thatÂ some latest pushed nodes are covered in one direction (newer to older) but not the other (older to newer).
Readers must be okay with this discrepancy, or ignore those nodes.
In our case, we use commit versioning and snapshots to ignore those nodes.
For such readers, the linked list can be read without a lock.
The pointer
{ newer -> new_node }
is finalized before the pointer
{ older -> new_node }
is finalized. Hence traversal in the newer direction is updated later. If and only if the job traverses from older to newer while searching for nodes to replace, then it is not possible to race the pushing of a node vs replacing the node being pushed.
